{{Infobox lake | name = Alajuela Lake | image = Lago Alajuela, Panama.jpg | caption = Natural-colour satellite image of Lake Alajuela | image_bathymetry = | caption_bathymetry = | location = [[Panamá]] | coords = {{Coord|9|14|04|N|79|34|32|W|type:waterbody_region:PA|display=title,inline}} | lake_type = [[Reservoir]] | inflow = | outflow = [[Panama Canal]] | catchment = {{convert|1026|km2|abbr=on}} | basin_countries = Panama | length = | width = | area = {{convert|50.2|km2|abbr=on}} | depth = | max-depth = | volume = ca. 600 hm<sup>3</sup> (750,000 ac ft<ref>{{cite journal |last=Hulman |first=Lewis G. |date=1972 |title=System Relationships a Panama Canal Water Supply Study |journal=Water Resources Research |volume=8 |issue=3 |pages=774–778 |doi=10.1029/WR008i003p00769 }}</ref>) | residence_time = | shore = | elevation = {{convert|76.8|m|ft|abbr=on}} | islands = | sections = | cities = | frozen = }} {{Location map|Panama|lat_dir=N|lat_deg=9|lat_min=12.669|lon_dir=W|lon_deg=79|lon_min=36.981|width=300|caption=Location within [[Panama]]|label=Lake Alajuela}}
'''Alajuela''' '''Lake''' ({{lang-es|Lago Alajuela}}) is an artificial lake on the [[Chagres River]] created by the [[Madden Dam]] and linked to the [[Panama Canal]]. Lake Alajuela serves as a [[reservoir]] for the canal, which lies to the lake’s southwest.<ref name="Earth Observatory" >{{cite web |title=Lago Alajuela, Panama |publisher=NASA |url=http://earthobservatory.nasa.gov/IOTD/view.php?id=48025 }}</ref> The Chagres, Pequení, Boquerón, Salamanca, La Puente, Indio, Piedras, San Cristóbal and Escandaloso rivers flow into the lake. The rivers of Lake Alajuela contribute 45 percent of the total water for the canal.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fundacionchagres.org/chagres-hidrologia.html |title=Parque Nacional Chagres: Hidrología |author=Fundación Parque Nacional Chagres |date= |work= |publisher= |accessdate=28 July 2012 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120509024221/http://www.fundacionchagres.org/chagres-hidrologia.html |archivedate=9 May 2012 }}</ref>
The reservoir was formerly known as Madden Lake when the [[Panama Canal Zone|Canal Zone]] was under U.S. administration and was renamed after control of the canal reverted to [[Panama]].<ref name="Earth Observatory" />
In early December 2010, Lake Alajuela reached its highest recorded water level, prompting authorities to close the Panama Canal for 17 hours.<ref name="Earth Observatory" /> The canal reopened on December 9.
