{{Orphan|date=July 2016}} {{Infobox medical condition (new) | name = <!--{{PAGENAME}} by default--> | synonym = | image = File:Adenopatía inguinal.png|thumb| | image_size = | alt = | caption = Inguinal lymphadenopathy | pronounce = | specialty = <!-- from Wikidata, can be overwritten --> | symptoms = | complications = | onset = | duration = | types = | causes = | risks = | diagnosis = | differential = | prevention = | treatment = | medication = | prognosis = | frequency = | deaths = }}
'''Inguinal lymphadenopathy''' causes [[swollen lymph nodes]] in the groin area. It can be a symptom of infective or neoplastic processes. Infective aetiologies include Tuberculosis, [[HIV]], non-specific or reactive lymphadenopathy to recent lower limb infection or groin infections. Another notable infectious cause is [[Lymphogranuloma venereum]], which is a sexually transmitted infection of the lymphatic system. Neoplastic aetiologies include [[lymphoma]], leukaemia and metastatic disease from primary tumours in the lower limb, external genitalia or perianal region and melanoma.
==References== * {{cite journal |author=Ferrer R |title=Lymphadenopathy: differential diagnosis and evaluation |journal=Am Fam Physician |volume=58 |issue=6 |pages=1313–20 |date=October 1998 |pmid=9803196 |doi= |url=http://www.aafp.org/afp/1998/1015/p1313.html }} ==Further reading== *{{cite book|title=Principles and Practice of Infectious Diseases|date=2014|publisher=Elsevier Health Sciences|isbn=9781455748013|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=BseNCgAAQBAJ&pg=PA2168&dq=inguinal+lymphadenopathy&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjcoN-h85nYAhUBPiYKHZ9KA6wQ6AEIPjAE#v=onepage&q=inguinal%20lymphadenopathy&f=false|accessdate=21 December 2017|language=en}}
